Rest of the group is generated by the above.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that this is a group, not a ring or a field.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 is not the complex 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, but just some group element.
 Some lemma and theorems:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\Gamma_{q,p}$
\end_inset

 one has 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{4}=I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{3}=i^{2}x$
\end_inset

 (Petitjean Lemma 2)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{q,p}$
\end_inset

 is a finite group with at most 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{q+p+2}$
\end_inset

 elements (Petitjean Theorem 2)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This appears to be a subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}_{4}\times\mbox{Cl}_{q,p}\left(\mathbb{R}\right)$
\end_inset

 in that there is a homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{a}\mapsto e_{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{2}\mapsto-1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $d=q+p$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $N=2^{\left\lfloor d/2\right\rfloor }$
\end_inset

.
 The gamma group can be represented by complex 
\begin_inset Formula $N\times N$
\end_inset

 matrices.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Gamma group is a p-group, with p=2.
 It is not a regular p-group.
 It is not a powerful p-group.
 The commutator subgroup 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\Gamma,\Gamma\right]=\left\{ I,i^{2}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The element 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 is not realliy needed, but is convenient, e.g.
 because the Pauli group is a representation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{3,0}$
\end_inset

 and it has an additional identitity: the chiral element is 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{1}\sigma_{2}\sigma_{3}=i$
\end_inset

.
 The gamma group is freer (its the free-est such!?)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Transpose (reversal)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Define the transpose 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(ab\right)^{t}=b^{t}a^{t}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in\Gamma_{q,p}$
\end_inset

.
 Then for a product of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 distinct generators 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\gamma_{a}\gamma_{b}\cdots\gamma_{c}\right)^{t}=\left(i^{2}\right)^{k\left(k-1\right)/2}\gamma_{a}\gamma_{b}\cdots\gamma_{c}
\]

\end_inset

This is (Petitjean Theorem 1).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Hermitian conjugation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What are all of the automorphisms of the gamma group? Dunno, but it seems
 we can define a daggar operation 
\begin_inset Formula $\dagger$
\end_inset

 that acts as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\gamma_{a}^{\dagger}=\begin{cases}
\gamma_{a} & \mbox{for }1\le a\le q\\
i^{2}\gamma_{a} & \mbox{for }q<a\le p+q
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

which is supplemented with 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{\dagger}=i^{3}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $I^{\dagger}=I$
\end_inset

.
 To avoid confusion with the usual Hermition conjugate, we also define 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(ab\right)^{\dagger}=b^{\dagger}a^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Charge conjugation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{p,q}$
\end_inset

 is isomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{p,q}^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

 and to 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{2}\Gamma_{p,q}$
\end_inset

 and to 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{2}\Gamma_{p,q}^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
No inner automorphisms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Transpose, charge conjugation and hermitian conjugation are not an inner
 automorphisms of the gamma group, and thus cannot be represented with group
 elements.
\end_layout

