\begin_layout Subsection
Chiral projections
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In 1+3 dimensions, 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{L}=\left(1-\gamma^{5}\right)/2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{R}=\left(1+\gamma^{5}\right)/2$
\end_inset

 and so in the Weyl basis 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{L}=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
I & 0\\
0 & 0
\end{array}\right)\quad\mbox{ and }\quad P_{R}=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
0 & 0\\
0 & I
\end{array}\right)
\]

\end_inset

so that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi=\left(\begin{array}{c}
\psi_{L}\\
\psi_{R}
\end{array}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
C-symmetry
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is more complicated.
 And confusing.
 So, for 3+1 dimensions, for the Dirac basis, the chiral(Weyl) basis and
 in the Majorana basis, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{0}\gamma^{k}\gamma^{0}=-\gamma^{k}=\left(\gamma^{k}\right)^{\dagger}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In 1+3 dimensions 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(+---\right)$
\end_inset

, the charge operator is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Q=\gamma^{0}
\]

\end_inset

its eigenstates are of a fixed charge.
 The charge conjugation matrix is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C\gamma_{\mu}C^{-1}=-\left(\gamma_{\mu}\right)^{T}
\]

\end_inset

for all representations.
 In all four bases (Dirac, Majorana, two chiral forms), 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{-1}=C^{\dagger}=C^{T}=-C$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The above is from Itzykson& Zuber, and also Bjorken&Drell, volume 2, page
 115.
 B&D Volume 1, page 67
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the Majorana basis, it is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C=-i\gamma^{0}
\]

\end_inset

which obeys 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{-1}=-C=C^{\dagger}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This works in the Majorana basis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the Dirac basis, 
\begin_inset Formula $C=i\gamma^{2}\gamma^{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{-1}=-C$
