\begin_layout Subsection
Lorentz group
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Write 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{\mu}=\left(1,\vec{\sigma}\right)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\sigma}$
\end_inset

 the usual Pauli matrices.
 This will provide the right-handed Weyl spinors.
 Write 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\mu\nu}=+---$
\end_inset

.
 Then we have also 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\sigma}^{\mu}=\left(1,-\vec{\sigma}\right)$
\end_inset

 which provides the left-handed spinors.
 Note the mind-numbing relations 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\sigma}^{\mu}=\sigma_{\mu}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The standard double-covering of orthochronous Lorentz group by 
\begin_inset Formula $S\in SL\left(2,\mathbb{C}\right)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\overline{\sigma}_{\mu}\Lambda_{\;\,\nu}^{\mu}=S\overline{\sigma}_{\nu}S^{\dagger}
\]

\end_inset

This works because it preserves the Minkowski metric: 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\mu}\mapsto x^{\prime\mu}=\Lambda_{\;\,\nu}^{\mu}x^{\nu}$
\end_inset

.
 That is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x^{\prime\mu}\overline{\sigma}_{\mu}=x^{\nu}\overline{\sigma}_{\mu}\Lambda_{\;\,\nu}^{\mu}=Sx^{\nu}\overline{\sigma}_{\nu}S^{\dagger}
\]

\end_inset

The above is called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the Weyl representation
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (of a point in Minkowski space).
 The conjugate version is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma_{\mu}\Lambda_{\;\,\nu}^{\mu}=\left(S^{-1}\right)^{\dagger}\sigma_{\nu}\left(S^{-1}\right)
\]

\end_inset

It is easier to just ditch the index notation: write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\overline{X}=\overline{\sigma}_{\mu}x^{\mu}=t+\vec{x}\cdot\vec{\sigma}\quad\quad X=\sigma_{\mu}x^{\mu}=t-\vec{x}\cdot\vec{\sigma}
\]

\end_inset

The product 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{X}X$
\end_inset

 is a Lorentz scalar, therefore the above is how things must transform.
 An alternate proof of this, using index notation, is given below.
\end_layout

