\begin_layout Subsection
Accidental isomorphims
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Time to be more careful.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First: 
\begin_inset Formula $O\left(p,q\right)$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

generalized orthogonal group
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 It preserves the quadratic form 
\begin_inset Formula $+---$
\end_inset

.
 It has four connected components.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{0}\left(O\left(p,q\right)\right)=C_{2}\times C_{2}=\mathbb{Z}_{2}\times\mathbb{Z}_{2}$
\end_inset

 the Klein four-group.
 Here 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{n}=\mathbb{Z}_{n}$
\end_inset

 is the cyclic group.
 The two factors flip the signs of the p,q basis vectors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next: 
\begin_inset Formula $SO\left(p,q\right)$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

special orthogonal group
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 It's elements have unit determinant.
 It has 2 connected components: 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{0}\left(SO\left(p,q\right)\right)=\mathbb{Z}_{2}=\left\{ \left(1,1\right),\left(-1,-1\right)\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $SO^{+}\left(p,q\right)$
\end_inset

 contains the identity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next 
\begin_inset Formula $U\left(n\right)=O\left(2n\right)\cap GL\left(n,\mathbb{C}\right)\cap Sp\left(2n,\mathbb{R}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Where symplectic means 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{T}JA=J$
\end_inset

 and complex means 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{-1}JA=J$
\end_inset

 and orthogonal means 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{T}=A^{-1}$
\end_inset

